          _cache[27] || (_cache[27] = createStaticVNode('<h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Lore</h2><h3 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Purple and Green are the nature of duality. Purple is ethereal, weblike essence that absorbs, detects, and authentically experiences. Green is direction, purpose, and engagement within the flow of positive action. Apollo and Dionysus, left and right, additive and subtractive, male and female, self and shadow. But a funny thing happens when instead of opposing and reflecting one another, they energize and focus one another. They amplify, they eclipse, they make love, they create. </h3><h4 data-v-bf2ea9f2>There is nothing like the feeling of writing a song on the guitar, recording and producing it like a full band, and then walking around town in the middle of the night listening to it on headphones to check the mastering. </h4><h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Early Material</h2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2><em data-v-bf2ea9f2>We were making Going With the Flow, rehearsing generally around 40 songs, ever changing, every single evening. There were hundreds of songs, generally adapted from demos or acoustic songs. We were just trying to get good, constantly rewriting everything, changing the style, adding tricks.</em></p><a href="https://thesteinsound.bandcamp.com/album/shades" target="_blank" data-v-bf2ea9f2><img class="stu-banner" alt="travels" src="' + _imports_1 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2></a><h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Travels (2010)</h2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2>The first set written for Stein. A concept album that evokes the tone of the psyche as it progresses throughout the day from morning to night. Rough around the edges, trying too hard, often silly, Travels nevertheless delivers surprisingly mature riffs and cerebral lyrics, undergirded with an insecure positivity vibe. </p><p data-v-bf2ea9f2>After completing Travels, Adam and Thilo moved to Portland, OR. It would be several years before they would have a place to rehearse again. There were many versions of Stein that existed in this period, including just Adam and a cellist. Adam played in other bands and continued making demos under the name Junk Tracks. </p><a href="https://thesteinsound.bandcamp.com/album/accidance-2" target="_blank" data-v-bf2ea9f2><img class="stu-banner" alt="accidance" src="' + _imports_2 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2></a><h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Accidance! (2015)</h2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2>A new chapter developed when Adam moved into an art house with a basement. The Flophouse was an environment of inclusion and social experimentation. Multiple bands of many genres rehearsed and performed in the basement, there were elaborate theme parties, gatherings based around fiction, poetry, filmmaking, and painting. Stein had become a family, a tribe of sensitive outcasts who liked to joke around and talk about ideas. Playing music was part of that. The music and media itself was crude, but we felt free to be ourselves, like we were not alone. </p><img class="stu-banner" alt="movies" src="' + _imports_3 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2> Accidance! was a movie on VHS and DVD, with videos for every song, each directed by a different person. We had raised money on kickstarter promising to &quot;swede&quot; suggested movies. We did Jurrasic Park, Northern Exposure, and Twin Peaks. It was kind of pointless. </p><a href="https://thesteinsound.bandcamp.com/album/shades" target="_blank" data-v-bf2ea9f2><img class="stu-banner" alt="shades" src="' + _imports_4 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2></a><h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Shades (2016)</h2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2>Stein moves in opposite directions, so the follow-up to DIY basement party was something emotionally challenging, delicate, and serious. Shades is a dreamy collection of &quot;black sheep&quot;, like deep cuts from non-existing bands. It created conflict to introduce a disciplined, high concept set with several ballads to a party dance band. What shines through is feminine, vulnerable, and thought-provoking, with moments of surreal beauty. The production and musicianship is competent. Shades is a mirror to Travels, tracing the psyche&#39;s course over the landscape of sleep. </p><img class="stu-banner" alt="shades banner" src="' + _imports_5 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2><h2 data-v-bf2ea9f2>Opposites Attract</h2><p data-v-bf2ea9f2> Stein had stuck together, and learned to be serious. A sort of sorry not sorry, comedy dance pop songs explicitly focused on sex. Stein was a business looking to market sex, with the hidden agenda of being a love cult. Sex is an analogy for love. The finished album currently sits unmastered on a Google drive. It was ridiculous. It took too long to make. Everyone moved on. </p><img class="stu-banner" alt="travels" src="' + _imports_6 + '" data-v-bf2ea9f2>', 21))
